About this hotel

Overlooking the Port of Barcelona, this upscale hotel near the Gothic Quarter dates from the 16th century. It's a 9-minute walk from the Drassanes metro station and 3 km from La Sagrada Familia.

Check-in time: 3:00 PM
Check-out time: 12:00 PM

    First thing is first- I chose this hotel after reading hundreds of reviews. Most of the 4/5 star reviews are accurate.

While we did not have an outside view, we did have a patio which was a really nice touch and made up for an indoor stateroom feel. The beds were super comfortable and the linens were soft. Between that and jet lag, we probably could have stayed in bed the entire trip (thank heavens we didn't!!). Also,this hotel is in the center of the action - Location, location, location!!

This is something that made me remove a star from my review even though the hotel was overall such a wonderful experience.
    You will want to go to the terrace and check out the views around sunset but will not want to waste your time trying to be served here. The IDGAF attitude from the server was apparent from the moment we asked a question. This is likely one aspect that prevents this from becoming a 5-star hotel (and I believe it's definitely possible).
    Another negative was that our room was just above the lobby and breakfast area and it gets really noisy in the morning. The rooms were advertised as soundproof but I can assure you that if you're on the first floor, you will hear the crowds... and it's quite possible they can hear you and whatever might be going on in your room... (couples beware). I am not sure how this can be fixed, but it is something worth noting for those who might want to request a room not on the first floor (the lobby is on 0).
    Nevertheless, I would stay here again without question and would recommend this hotel to anyone who is thinking about a trip to Barcelona. The location, clean rooms, quality linen, and hotel staff make this one of the better hotels I've stayed at.

    Gothic Quarter

    The charming Gothic Quarter, or Barri Gòtic, has narrow medieval streets filled with trendy bars, clubs and Catalan restaurants. The Museu d'Història de Barcelona shows remains of the Roman city. Artisans sell leather and jewelry near the Cathedral of Barcelona, while flower stalls and street-food vendors line busy avenue La Rambla. The Plaça del Pi, named after the adjacent Gothic church, hosts a weekend art market.

    About this hotel

    Overlooking the Port of Barcelona, this upscale hotel near the Gothic Quarter dates from the 16th century. It's a 9-minute walk from the Drassanes metro station and 3 km from La Sagrada Familia.…

    Offering free Wi-Fi, the sleek rooms have flat-screen TVs, minibars, and tea and coffeemaking equipment. Suites add sitting areas and Nespresso machines. Some upgraded rooms have private balconies.

    There's a sophisticated restaurant with period features, a restaurant offering a terrace with port views, and a cocktail bar. Other amenities include a rooftop sundeck with a plunge pool, plus meeting and event space.
